Inflation in Europe falls on food
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 eurozone countries was greater than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office located in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the direct interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and lower unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below but close to 2 percent.
According to one analyst, this is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "it is necessary to deter" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the eurozone has dropped due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market quotas increased by 88 percent and soybean price also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, global oil prices rose by 52 percent and last month a barrel of black gold cost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 percent but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the inflation rate over 12 months remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the key interest rate twice in 2008.
Gallup Signs Government Crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December.So since 2002, it currently has the highest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Survey) has never seen such a low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For the loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
On the faithful voters certain to go vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who judged that the economic situation of the country was serious has never been so high, it rises to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population anticipates an aggravation and only a tenth anticipates an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of people surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, thought the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the prime minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year, 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, at present this rate represents only 20 percent.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would definitely vote and another 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would participate and 15 percent additional would likely participate. Following current intentions, the outcome of the referendum would have no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to enrollment fees in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital spending.
When we look only at the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters, respectively, would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital spending.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco increased its prices by 20 percent
The hypermarkets located in the commercial triangle of Budaörsined the average price increase of 16 percent from last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article from Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “which had already flown” in major grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003 this value was 6 800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year’s level, but the prices of turkey nuts, nuts and peaches have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but at Auchan, one kilogram of bread was found at only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the ordered bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the ordered bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Cart, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we find a difference of 12 percent while the difference between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,484 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year’s Christmas prices.
This process confused trade, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products because they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin tailored to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the price of the Daily basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher by 1 720 forints than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest rose by 1,284 forints as well.
By bringing the two seasons closer to Christmas, we saw a catastrophic price rise, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods rose by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foods, the statistical institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
This seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has risen by barely more than 10 percent from the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get multinational companies to accept the sharp price hike as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets they visit.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-lasting foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, significant queues were formed at the box office of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased abruptly.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they are not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by improper use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also make savings on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the János Hospital traumatology department.
Antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man who was hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return there due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do a major operation because of the bacteria that is in his body.
As of December 10, this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Center for Epidemiology.
That is, the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium in their nose without developing any disease.
SA-caused infections (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant antibiotic bacterium that will proliferate quickly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, low-weight or weakened patients.
According to the head doctor of the hospital János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
We should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA alone or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
They are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, care staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have suitable antibiotics to treat them,” Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion.
The vast majority of MRSA-caused infections could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Because this infection is most common in hospitals and residential homes for the elderly, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only emerge if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief medical officer of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations regarding the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and primary care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs spread from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore crucial to wash hands, wear gloves and protective masks.H, significant gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact, however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemics, the sick should be kept at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save on disinfectants, lack nurses, there are many sick people, so the risk of contamination is even greater, Karolina Böröcz said.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
The Government's Project Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to the published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The police officer, who committed a fatal accident, was not drunk.
The official statement concerning the fatal accident caused by the commissary of the 22nd district has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the 22nd district commissioner, who has resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, Attila Morvai, a spokeswoman for the capital's public prosecutor's office, said on Friday after the relative finding was established.
The findings confirmed the first outcome of the investigation that already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before taking the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former 22nd district police chief crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, on 22nd district Kossuth Lajos Street.
(Furthermore, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian passage is not an mitigating circumstance, according to the Road Code a car that begins a curve must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the commissioner resigned from his position and requested his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident has greatly upset him.
The case is being investigated by the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the outset with the magistrates in charge of conducting the investigation.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements worth a total of €400 million on a loan line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of €300 million for Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund, with a loan agreement of €100 million already signed by the parties.
The €150 million loan agreement also covers the budget financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of €300 million for Hungary, the remaining €150 million can be used later, following the extension of the loan agreement.
The parties signed a contract of €50 million for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the subway line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would reconsider the possible modification of the original contract once Hungary has finalised the details of the subway financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has allocated a total of €8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its credits at the EURIBOR interest rate, with a limitation period of 8 years and no commitment commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate market of the EU
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little cited in the past.
What, or and who bought in this EU market that is still the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable destination in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly in search of a building in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly many to buy in the very inexpensive corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, shops and office areas promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf havens in Europe and thus a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy a building in Bulgaria at the same time seek to change their lives, their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea shores and in the most reputable ski resorts, we traditionally meet a lot of Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old broken houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary homes (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving value-added in the medium or long term.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly rising due to an increasing demand.
In the European Union, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in property prices largely exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which should define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emissions reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions between developing countries and developed countries on this subject.
The United States also that at the moment it does not want to discuss exact figures, but was ready to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed, in addition to emissions reduction, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors composed of 16 members likely within the framework of the UN Global Fund for the Environment (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
6% of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Water, confirms the EU’s ambition to retain its role as an admiral vessel in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the successful signing of the “Agreement after 2012”, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also willing to take commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signing the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 percent and all 15 member states of the EU at that time made the commitment of 8 percent less.
Hungary has pledged to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, the Ministry of the Environment said in a press release.
The challenge is great in Bali as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be implemented within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would be postponed after 2012.In this case, reduction commitments below the values set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not immediately be followed by a new international emission reduction system whose necessity was stressed in the new report of the IPCC, the international scientific body, which won the Nobel Peace Prize of the United Nations, in charge of dealing with climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and an increase in Earth’s average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British military units share on the video sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to make themselves popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has become passionate about YouTube: the special units intervening in Afghanistan upload videos there on the operations carried out against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with the help of miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable.
The air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defense registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and publishes videos of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the air force's initial goal, the videos were posted on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defense, they also served to make the general public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published by this route costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, said Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, to the BBC.
The Americans played a game.
The army is upset because, in addition to the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have passed onto the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in “official” propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, officers don’t avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real missions, but the British army has only recently embarked on loading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the America's Army shooting game downloadable for free.In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
