The mega strike forces are gathering.
The League’s unions and the National Association of Workers’ Councils will constitute their strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday’s indefinite strike.
A general protest assembly will be held on Saturday and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This action will cause significant traffic jams as railway traffic will be almost completely stopped and employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 13:00.
The League’s trade unions will announce on Friday afternoon the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers’ Councils.
The LIGA-MOSZ strike commission will also be formed, serving as the coordinator of Monday’s actions.
A general protest assembly will be held on Saturday and, starting Monday, organisations joining the strike will stop working indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not pass the law on health funds, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the National Assembly’s Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the health funds law will only take place late in the evening, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, significant traffic congestion is planned: railways will stop work indefinitely and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being shut down.
At the same time, in different points of the country, half the road will also be blocked.
Many unions and civil society organizations have joined the strike call, the list of which is constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some organizations report to go on strike indefinitely, others have declared a temporary shutdown.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Railroad Syndicate (VDSZSZ) have failed to reach an agreement on the minimum services, but, as Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest’s public transport will strike from the start of service until 13:00, the Budapest airport between 7 and 9 am, the Electricity and Thermal Energy Industry Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers’ Union and the Democratic Teachers’ Union have called for a strike for 2 hours and 2 hours to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will go on strike across the country alternately, while the Syndicate of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ) affiliated with the SZEF will go on a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, formulated by the League, demands that the government withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires the new method of calculating pensions to be introduced from next year to be introduced in several stages.
The third claim wants a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that would allow the functions that deserve it to pass into the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Railroad Workers’ Union (VDSZSZ), affiliated with the League’s Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport regarding secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increased Country Risk
According to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, established last August, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its “risk warning”, the company points out that, in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the biggest political risk is already that “in the short term aggressive ethnic confrontations may occur as a result of the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Zigeon and non-Zigeon population of Hungary”.
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main gaps of Hungarian political actors: “public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians.”
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are being strengthened and the advent of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the effect of the increased attention of Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been established in Hungary since the summer of 2007 giving themselves the name of "National Association of Self-Defense".
“The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civil organization while they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defense missions (catastrophes, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, in addition, evoking the incompetence of the police, the army, that is, the state,” they added.
They that everything was going according to the method that, based on the resentment of society from politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civil aspect.
The emphasis on the civil character and association status is therefore only used to avoid the legal traps of registering these associations in court, but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighbourhood relations.
In recent months, many neighboring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and ultranationalist political actors in some neighboring countries have sought to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This affects the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, political risks have increased across the region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard resembles, for example, the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The numerous Roma riots that broke out in a neighborhood of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) are at the origin of the constitution of the Bulgarian guard.
