In Hungary, the law precisely defines holidays and, around holidays, it has become commonplace to reorganize working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and days of rest.
Holidays are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter especially so that the awakeners can rest peacefully.
In one year, there are 11 festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 also which is the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On 20 August we celebrate the constitution of our state, on 1 May is Labor Day and on 1 and 2 November we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, we have two days in Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday preceding the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has decided in a special regulation on the replacement days of days before or after holidays.
The law extends to all employers and to all their employees employed, to officials and to persons working in the public service.
It does not apply, however, to service companies, to institutions that are constantly operating and in service, because of their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, working days will change only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life almost stops across the country because according to experiences most people rather do overtime or take holidays they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, therefore there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around the work day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
