Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of England, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be placed on the currency markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
As an example, the U.S. Federal Reserve will auction $40 billion and, in addition, provide $24 billion to European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual states have decided on such a concerted action, aimed at preventing or even mitigating the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," writes Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group in his customer report.
"The concerted action of central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts expect additional billions of dollars.
“If central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they have to really understand what can still follow,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“He says the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would lower consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after they failed to lower London’s interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual loans, despite the U.S., Canadian and British central banks having repeatedly lowered their interest rates during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central bank’s move will not contribute to conjuring the crisis, as it does not solve the main problem that is the fall in the U.S. real estate market.
