Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your holidays can come true if you make a good choice.
Gold and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or drunk cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean, you will find this list not only in its entirety, but enriched.
However, there is only one island on which you will find much more and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the warehouse and place of transfer of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920s.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the heads of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the US (especially under the ban) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner and Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings rose and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 1950s of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco from Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he owned his yacht.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
And today then?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita in Havana.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be mixed the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars are still circulating in Havana, since the jigoles and fiats once imported have long since rotted in such a salty and humid climate.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is significantly degraded, nowhere else in the vicinity there are as many splendid colonial monuments as there are exactly there.
Other places are becoming more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings money if necessary, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the province of Holguín, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had come back from the plantations spread out in the candy shops on a narrow path by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how you can see small locomotives running there, whose contemporaries are not found elsewhere only in museums.
Where to direct your footsteps?
Most visitors do not miss the most famous places.
Therefore, there is no need to write a lot about Varadero or Havana.
Other than reminding that in the Hemingway property, already mentioned, there is a museum and that those who love this writer should not miss the visit.
The Viňales Valley to the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
An exuberant vegetation grows there on a limestone soil.
Mogots, limestone balloons and rocks rise in candlestick from the bottom of the valley, and, fertile soil having grabbed into their intestines, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetable carpet.
The valley is probably the place where the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can encounter the final shape of this product if you visit one of Havana’s cigars factories.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was filmed.
Trinidad
Ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar market that brought him glory and wealth.
Wealth was embodied in the beauty and city-vitrine character of this small-size city.
Koloniální španělská architektura,výrazně ovlivněna pozdějšími francouzskými osadníky, has almost not changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the mountainous massive Escambray, is a place so far apart that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay away.
Nothing was built, and therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was content to have a roof over his head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is also worth going to see interesting places in the vicinity, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the Valley of Sucre.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música, which is animated after sunset and where the music is obscured only in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some designate this town located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is already influenced by the path that leads there.
The two roads leading there from Guantanamo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross a landscape almost without traces of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed the East of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in fact, it was born about a hundred years after the journey of Columbus) and from the hill where the former castle-fort and the current hotel El Castillo stands, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the mountain massif Sierra Maestra, the Bay of Truies and the island of Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patroness of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of the former slaves, about all this one could fill a number of pages.
But, as they say, it’s better to see once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, Americans say
The shortage of soldiers and the necessary equipment influences, according to the United States, on the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland, representatives of countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to the growing opposition from the Taliban movement, the eight countries involved are now also discussing future plans and allied coordination.
While the United States this week through Defense Secretary Robert Gates called on NATO troops to be more active, Britain sees as a priority the strengthening of the Afghan government’s authority and the intensification of development aid.
“The developments in Afghanistan are noticeable, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," Defense Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
90 percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent acts has increased by 27 percent from last year, to 60 percent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, a quarter of them in the south.
However, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are asking for additional helicopters, soldiers and experts for the training of Afghan troops.
“We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as the ways to them,” Gates said.
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop made a similar statement.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about 90 percent of the troops and equipment we would need, and that’s not enough,” De Hoop told Reuters at the end of the three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
who is passive
In recent months, conflicts have also been raised between the countries involved on whether all allies are actually doing their best in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the fighting requirements they are subject to are not as strict as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate," Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun called this week the German soldiers lazy.
“Afghan swindlers discovered: the Germans are playing, while ours are fighting,” Sun wrote in a document supplemented by pictures of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild went to counterattack by publishing a photo of a British troop during a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
Government debt to reach $1 billion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 crowns shall be borne by each Czech citizen.
The total debt rose at the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
Thanks to a better than expected development of the state budget savings, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
Thus, in the nine months of this year it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
As of June, it fell by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the state debt from early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns is borne by each Czech citizen.
Over the past year, the state owed more than 111 billion crowns.
"For now, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could exceed the one trillion crown limit only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns,” said Patria Finance analyst David Marek to the server iHNed.cz.
The forecast of Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor is similar: “We could exceed the billion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget, which is not yet known.
If it turned out that the situation on the political scene was changing, that politicians were willing to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I don’t expect this change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The state debt is constituted by the central government debt and is generated mainly by the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bonds, rent securities, direct loans or, for example, by loans to the European Investment Bank.
The state’s domestic debt has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state’s external debt has increased this year from 1.7 billion to 123.3 billion.
The state’s so-called negotiable debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and decreased by 13.7 billion crowns from June.
The average state debt requirement was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased annually from the first half to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a much too high figure.
Interestingly, the increase is generated mainly by rent securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be material to negotiate when the pension reform comes," Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
It follows from the government’s financing and debt management strategy for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better than expected development of the state budget savings, the ministry reduced the planned sum to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the state budget, which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns initially planned.
The following are the maximum sources planned for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion SEK, the reserve of 10 billion SEK for pension payments, the financing of state pension securities of 43 billion SEK and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank of 1.8 billion SEK.
