The Serbs and Albanians of Kosovo concluded on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, a sixth and final session of talks without being able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a news conference in Vienna.
Underlining that peace in the region is "on the stake", its U.S. counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
"We do not anticipate violence right now, but we are entering a very difficult period," he said, adding that "evident tensions exist."
The end of the mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ishinger, Wisner and Russian Ombudsman Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The Baden talks, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was commissioned a new mediation by the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans believe their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council's granting of independence to Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence.
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, the West believes that independence under the supervision of the EU is the only viable solution.
Pristina says it is ready to unilaterally proclaim it if the Security Council does not decide in its favor.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," President Fatmir Sejdiu of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority said in the hotel in Baden, where the "last chance negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed his regrets.
But he added that the autonomous plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations."
