Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise is still feasible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence.
Belgrade says it fears a “domino effect” in a region still weakened by the 1990s independence wars.
"For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
"The European Parliament will have the last word"
"Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they started: in the Security Council.”
To reporters, Fatmir Sedjiu responded that "the parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanian speakers would be made "in consultation" with the West.
