After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only accessible for a “humanitarian” purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or its rightful successors.
The eleven states in charge of their management – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
