The climate of Venus could reveal the future of the Earth.
Scientists said yesterday that Venus was a pleasant planet to live on.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit showed that the planet is twice as small as Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are virtually the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus might have had conditions similar to those of Earth, and could even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, the atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation coupled with a slower rotation led Venus to a whole other kind of evolution.
Today the planet is deprived of water, is devastated by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead.
The discoveries of Venus Express, the European Space Agency’s probe, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of the Earth’s potential future due to catastrophic climate change.
Oxford University physics professor Fred Taylor, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “We are beginning to understand why Venus’s climate is so different from Earth’s, although the planets themselves are virtually similar.
“Our new data allows us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to Earth, even with a habitable surface.”
