Venus is the Infernal Twin of Earth.
Despite its life-hostile atmosphere, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turns at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today proved this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus burst at an altitude of about 56 kilometers of cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life has existed, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be Earth’s infernal twin, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venus's search, as no more spacecraft had been on its way for the exploration of this planet since the 1980s.
According to the researchers, the most recent results of research that have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the points in common with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than initially assumed.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the wind turbulence already known at the north pole, a turbulence of clouds at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet, called the evening or morning star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower on itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bars, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed in similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost into space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
