These are not Warhol’s boxes.
Whoever connects the concept of Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Right now, wooden boxes made in Sweden throw shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Much of the eighty-ten Brillo-Boxs of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today results in a disappointing result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as much of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first “Brillo-Boxes”, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the powdered soap cartons “Brillo”.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 – with the agreement of Warhol – hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
It was not about artworks here, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses from the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered right into the history of art and auctions, as Andy Warhol's original Brillo-Boxes licensed, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have ceded to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were produced in Malmö only in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
