The rebel troops of Manila
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers are giving up, the same ones who had stuck in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
Soldiers who were loyal to the government had assaulted the hotel with tear gas.
Two dozen soldiers had been stuck in the building for hours.
About half of them stood before the courts on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclips with about 30 supporters.
The military policemen, who normally had to watch them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his riot.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to power closed the sector around the respectable hotel.
He called for an urgent meeting of the Security Council.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People are tired of it,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded the elite unit of the Scouts Rangers, said other units in the army would soon want to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a massive protest against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila has been the scene of the roughly 200-member army uprising against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurgency broke out almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
